.TH GIT-CLEANUP-REPO 1 "2026-06-13" "git-tools" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
git-cleanup-repo \- clean stale local branches and worktrees
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B git cleanup-repo
.RI [ options ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B git cleanup-repo
fetches and prunes the remote, updates the repository default branch, then
deletes stale local branches.
.PP
By default it deletes local branches that are already merged into the base
branch. This includes squash- and rebase-merged branches: the branch's
collapsed diff is compared against the base by patch-id, so a clean squash merge
is recognized as merged even though its commits are not ancestors of the base.
It can also delete branches whose upstream is gone or every local branch except
the base branch.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-b ", " \-\-base " " \fIbranch\fR
Base branch to keep and update.
.TP
.BR \-r ", " \-\-remote " " \fIname\fR
Remote to fetch and pull from. Defaults to
.BR origin .
.TP
.B \-\-gone
Also delete branches whose upstream is gone.
.TP
.BR \-a ", " \-\-all
Delete all local branches except the base branch.
.TP
.B \-\-remove\-worktrees
Remove clean linked worktrees for deleted branches.
.TP
.BR \-n ", " \-\-dry\-run
Print actions without changing anything.
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Show help.
.SH SAFETY
The command refuses to run with a dirty current worktree or active
rebase, merge, cherry-pick, or revert state. Linked worktrees are skipped by
default unless
.B \-\-remove\-worktrees
is given and the worktree is clean.
